  <text>
    <body>
      <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.3514" xml:lang="en">
        <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
        <dateline>Lista de Correos, Barcelona. Christmas day 1894.</dateline>
        <opener>Dear D<hi rendition="#sup">r</hi>. H. Schuchardt, </opener>

        <p>I write to wish you a happy new year. May it lead to better things for Basque. On page 538 of your last separat-abdruck I find <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">ahaidego &amp; edergo</hi>
          </foreign> – but I do not find these words in Aizkibels dictionary – When you mention <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Baiae and Uroneko</hi>

          </foreign>, were you not thinking of a certain postcard that I sent you from somewhere near the Minho last autumn? Your train of thought at least reminds me of mine own, which I think I communicated to you. My address will probably be <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Barcelona, en lista</hi>, till the 8<hi
            rendition="#sup">th</hi> Is Arabic <hi rend="unknown"
            rendition="#none">maidah</hi> the father of Basque <foreign xml:lang="eu">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
maya</hi>
          </foreign> the table? Simonet thinks the latter comes from <foreign xml:lang="la">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">mensa</hi>
          </foreign>, as I proposed out of my inner consciousness in the <ref
            target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.5676">Euskal erria</ref> in 1888 or 89. Is my etymology of <foreign xml:lang="pt">
            <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">
aps</hi>
          </foreign> in Portuguese the right one? <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Apex</hi> as in S<hi
            rendition="#sup">t</hi> Jeromes Bible? There are a few more of my questions, I think, awaiting your answer or criticism. I have from the first, 1886 though Basque sal must be a purchase from English. We occupied French Basque land for centuries and linguistically there was then more solidarity among all the Basques as they then had more territory &amp; less knowledge of <hi
            rend="unknown" rendition="#none">romance</hi>.</p>
        <closer>
          <salute>Yours truly</salute>
          <signed>
            <persName ref="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.persons#P.1402">E. S. Dodgson</persName>.</signed>
        </closer>
        <postscript>
          <p>
            <note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der linken Seite.</note> Is marraina the same as mahaina? as one book has it.</p>
          <p>
            <note n="2" place="foot" type="editorial">Randnotiz auf der rechten Seite.</note> more misprints in R. de L. for Oct: fancy calling Sard a patois!</p>
          <p>
            <note n="3" place="foot" type="editorial">Kopfüber am oberen Rand geschrieben.</note> “documents” should be, as I wrote, “inscriptions”. </p>
        </postscript>
        <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
      </div>
